---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import { Picture } from "astro:assets";
import blog001 from "../images/blog001.jpg";
---

<Layout title="Tacit Labs">
    <main class="p-gutter flex flex-col min-h-dvh">
        <div class="grid gap-gutter grid-cols-12 mt-24 min-[810px]:mt-50">

            <!-- TOC sidebar — visible only at 1200px+ where there's room -->
            <aside class="hidden min-[1200px]:flex col-start-1 col-span-3 flex-col gap-6 sticky top-20 self-start pl-[98px]">
                <p class="font-mono font-light text-xs uppercase text-black/40">Contents</p>
                <a href="#search-algorithms" class="toc-link font-mono font-light text-[11px] leading-[150%] text-black/30 pl-3 border-l border-transparent transition-colors duration-200">
                    Biotech companies are inefficient search algorithms and biological experiments are expensive verifiers
                </a>
                <a href="#agentic-systems" class="toc-link font-mono font-light text-[11px] leading-[150%] text-black/30 pl-3 border-l border-transparent transition-colors duration-200">
                    Agentic systems are making search parallelizable and computational models for chemistry and biology are making verification fast and cheap
                </a>
                <a href="#compute-not-headcount" class="toc-link font-mono font-light text-[11px] leading-[150%] text-black/30 pl-3 border-l border-transparent transition-colors duration-200">
                    The next generation of biotech companies will scale with compute, not headcount
                </a>
                <a href="#tacit-infrastructure" class="toc-link font-mono font-light text-[11px] leading-[150%] text-black/30 pl-3 border-l border-transparent transition-colors duration-200">
                    Tacit Labs is building infrastructure to enable this kind of company
                </a>
                <a href="#zero-person-biotechs" class="toc-link font-mono font-light text-[11px] leading-[150%] text-black/30 pl-3 border-l border-transparent transition-colors duration-200">
                    Towards one million zero-person biotechs
                </a>
            </aside>

            <!-- Main content -->
            <div
                class="col-span-12 min-[640px]:col-span-8 min-[640px]:col-start-3 min-[810px]:col-span-6 min-[810px]:col-start-4 min-[1200px]:col-span-4 min-[1200px]:col-start-5 flex flex-col"
            >
                <div class="flex flex-col gap-6 text-center">
                    <h1 class="font-display text-lg leading-[130%]">
                        Introducing<br />
                        Tacit Labs
                    </h1>
                    <p class="font-mono font-light uppercase text-xs">
                        by Nicole Fitzgerald & Anne Marie Droste
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="flex flex-col gap-gutter">
                    <div class="aspect-8/5 w-full h-auto overflow-clip p-8">
                        <Picture
                            src={blog001}
                            alt="Headshot"
                            class="w-full h-full object-cover"
                        />
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="text-[15px] tracking-[1%] font-display leading-[150%] px-gutter min-[810px]:px-0 pb-30 min-[810px]:pb-50 flex flex-col gap-4">
                    <p>
                    Biology offers greater potential to improve human life than any other scientific domain.
                    It's also the most complex — demanding measurement, integration, and reasoning across multiple scales,
                    over hundreds of variables interacting simultaneously within systems we still only partially understand.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                    The ultimate test of our understanding is our ability to systematically intervene on those systems
                    without destabilizing the whole — that is, to identify a biological mechanism, create a drug against it,
                    and cure a disease in a human being. The problem is that reaching this test (clinical proof-of-concept in humans)
                    takes approximately 10 years and typically costs around $100M.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                    Large-scale reasoning systems have progressed most rapidly in domains where data and verification are cheap
                    and abundant. In code, a proposed solution can be executed against tests, checked by a compiler, benchmarked
                    for performance, or evaluated in a sandbox. In math, formal systems like Lean can turn proofs into machine-checkable
                    objects, where each step must satisfy the rules of the system. The feedback is not perfect, and it does not cover
                    all scientific reasoning, but it is cheap, repeatable, and tightly coupled to the task.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                    Biology does not yet have an equivalent loop. We founded Tacit to build that loop, unlocking faster, denser feedback
                    for large-scale agentic systems to train and deploy on the full gamut of drug discovery and development. We are starting
                    with designing long-horizon evaluations across this pipeline [link to OAI] and will systematically build out the tooling,
                    data and infrastructure to enable autonomous drug development at scale.
                    </p>

                    <h2 id="search-algorithms" class="font-display text-lg leading-[130%] text-left mt-4">Biotech companies are inefficient search algorithms and biological experiments are expensive verifiers</h2>
                    <p>
                        Making a drug requires searching through a space of dependent choices: target, modality, molecule, assay,
                        biomarker, patient population, and development path. Each decision constrains the next, and a single wrong
                        assumption can invalidate the chain. The form factor of today's biotech companies is ill-suited to search
                        across the full space of possible drug programs. The company itself is already a commitment: to a thesis, a team,
                        a platform, a set of tools, and a narrow region of biological possibility. Exploring another branch often means
                        assembling different expertise, running different experiments, finding different vendors, and raising more capital.
                        In other words, we run a slow, process-heavy, sequential search algorithm, where changing course often means
                        rebuilding from an earlier assumption.
                    </p>

                    <p>The feedback loop is just as difficult. Drug development does not have a cheap test that says whether a
                        program is right. It has a sequence of proxies, each more expensive than the last, and each only partially
                        predictive of the answer that matters. A molecule can bind cleanly and fail in cells. It can work in cells
                        and fail in animals. It can work in animals and fail in humans. It can look safe in early studies and
                        fail when tested in the right patients, at the right dose, over the right time horizon. The strongest
                        verifier is human biology, and it arrives late. Until then, teams are forced to make expensive decisions
                        from incomplete signals.
                    </p>

                    <h2 id="agentic-systems" class="font-display text-lg leading-[130%] text-left mt-4">Agentic systems are making search parallelizable and computational models for chemistry and biology are making verification fast and cheap
                    </h2>

                    <p>
                        AI changes both sides of the problem. Reasoning models and agents make search less constrained by the
                        team a company has hired. Instead of one narrow group exploring one narrow path, a system can instantiate
                        many forms of expertise in parallel: chemist, biologist, translational scientist, clinical strategist.
                        It can read more, branch more, preserve more context, and compare more possible paths before committing
                        scarce evidence.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Computational chemistry models and human biology models change the feedback side of the loop. They
                        compress large histories of experiments into in silico signals: how molecules bind, fold, clear,
                        distribute, and fail; how cells, pathways, tissues, and patients respond under different conditions.
                        They do not replace the wet lab or the clinic. But they let more of the search happen against learned
                        approximations of biology and chemistry, allowing agentic systems to quickly and cheaply garner signal
                        along their path, backtrack if necessary, and orient towards the most promising routes before the strongest,
                        most expensive verifiers are invoked.
                    </p>
                    <h2 id="compute-not-headcount" class="font-display text-lg leading-[130%] text-left mt-4">The next generation of biotech companies will scale with compute, not headcount</h2>
                    <p>In the limit, these forces compress drug discovery and development to a function of data, compute, 
                        experiments, and token spend. The shape of company that will bring the next generation of drugs to 
                        market will look fundamentally different as a result — model-centric, massively parallelized, and 
                        increasingly autonomous. 
                    </p>

                    <p>Compute will touch every consequential decision in the pipeline: what product to build; which 
                        biology to trust; what experiments to run, how they should be orchestrated, and how to interpret 
                        the results; which molecules or modalities to advance; when to stop; which patients to enroll, 
                        and how to design the trial. A single person equipped with a laptop and a credit card will be 
                        able to specify a disease area, target, or therapeutic hypothesis, then spin up agentic 
                        systems to explore the surrounding program space. 
                    </p>

                    <p>Once a search is specified in software, the bandwidth a single scientist has to spend tending it
                         drops sharply, and programs that once ran sequentially can run side by side. As each program increases
                          in autonomy, its marginal cost falls, increasing the total number of concurrent programs that can be run 
                          under a fixed cost. Furthermore, this paradigm allows insight uncovered by each program to be shared 
                          across the whole portfolio — positive results, negative results, and outstanding ambiguity. Each cycle 
                          refines direction, raises the quality of the next hypothesis, and lifts its probability of success. This
                          accumulates a base of compounding knowledge that cannot exist in the sequential model.</p>

                    <h2 id="tacit-infrastructure" class="font-display text-lg leading-[130%] text-left mt-4">Tacit Labs is building infrastructure to enable this kind of company</h2>
                    <h2 id="zero-person-biotechs" class="font-display text-lg leading-[130%] text-left mt-4">Towards one million zero-person biotechs</h2>
                    <p>
                    We are a team of researchers, engineers, scientists, and operators
                    who have trained frontier language models, designed and scaled
                    experimental platforms, and brought drugs to the clinic. We are
                    actively <span
                        ><a class="underline" href="/join-us">hiring.</a></span
                    >
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    </main>
</Layout>

<style>
    .toc-link.active {
        color: black !important;
        border-left-color: black !important;
    }
    .toc-link:hover {
        color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.7);
    }
</style>

<script>
    const headings = document.querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>('h2[id]');
    const tocLinks = document.querySelectorAll<HTMLAnchorElement>('.toc-link');

    const observer = new IntersectionObserver(
        (entries) => {
            entries.forEach(entry => {
                if (entry.isIntersecting) {
                    tocLinks.forEach(link => link.classList.remove('active'));
                    const active = document.querySelector<HTMLElement>(`.toc-link[href="#${entry.target.id}"]`);
                    active?.classList.add('active');
                }
            });
        },
        { rootMargin: '-10% 0px -80% 0px', threshold: 0 }
    );

    headings.forEach(h => observer.observe(h));
</script>
